                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d410">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/1408</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Chargé
                            <persName type="to">Mayer</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-09-27T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 27, 1916, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your September 4, 2 p.m. Departments of State and Navy concur in opinion that
                    until administration of the civil positions created by treaty is satisfactorily
                    and permanently installed and constabulary permanently equipped for efficient
                    service, such institutions as are still inefficient should remain under control
                    of occupation. The several officials appointed by treaty should be constantly
                    consulted.</p>
                <p>Sanitation should properly fall under supervision of Oberlin, pursuant to
                    stipulations Article XIII of Treaty, unless he desires cooperation of, or
                    control by, occupation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
